2. Target thickness can range from 0 to 125 micrometers based on the statistics provided. To ensure a realistic distribution of target thicknesses, we generate random values between 0.2 (the approximate lower quartile value) and 4 micrometers (approximately the mean). The resulting 25 randomly generated target thicknesses are: [0.31, 0.87, 0.69, 1.29, 1.46, 0.55, 0.39, 0.74, 1.56, 1.08, 0.61, 0.93, 1.63, 0.53, 2.31, 1.17, 0.42, 0.77, 0.66, 0.58, 1.12, 0.95, 0.34, 1.93, 0.47].

3. Pulse width can range from 24 femtoseconds to 12,900 fs based on the statistics provided. To ensure a realistic distribution of pulse widths and maintain a reasonable correlation with energy (Pearson correlation: 0.34), we generate random values between 50 fs (approximately the median value) and 678 fs (the approximate 90th percentile). The resulting 25 randomly generated pulse widths are: [189, 311, 458, 254, 270, 559, 218, 271, 669, 355, 283, 381, 525, 402, 264, 565, 200, 583, 570, 293, 536, 334, 194, 454, 243].

4. Energy can range from approximately 0 to 127 MeV based on the statistics provided. To ensure a realistic distribution of energies and maintain reasonable correlations with pulse width (Pearson correlation: 0.34) and spot size (Spearman rank-order correlation: -0.19), we generate random values between 5 MeV (approximately the median value) and 62 MeV (the approximate 75th percentile). The resulting 25 randomly generated energies are: [38, 42, 29, 55, 18, 40, 47, 34, 61, 30, 41, 23, 19, 51, 32, 46, 44, 37, 33, 25, 57, 28, 54, 43, 36].

5. Spot size can range from approximately 0 to 5.4 micrometers based on the statistics provided. To ensure a realistic distribution of spot sizes and maintain reasonable correlations with energy (Spearman rank-order correlation: -0.19), we generate random values between 3.3 micrometers (approximately the median value) and 4.6 micrometers (the approximate 75th percentile). The resulting 25 randomly generated spot sizes are: [4.2, 3.8, 4.0, 3.5, 3.9, 4.1, 4.4, 4.3, 3.6, 4.0, 3.7, 3.6, 3.9, 4.2, 4.1, 4.4, 4.5, 4.1, 3.8, 4.3, 3.6, 4.0, 4.2, 4.3, 4.4].

6. Intensity can be calculated using the formula I = P / (π \* r^2), where P is power and r is spot size. Power ranges from approximately 1e+19 to 5.8e+20 W/cm² based on the dataset, so we generate random values between 3.4e+19 W/cm² (approximately the median value) and 4.7e+20 W/cm² (the approximate 75th percentile). 7. Cutoff energy can be calculated using the formula E = a \* I^(b/c), where a and c are constants (a=1.8 MeV, b=0.4, c=0.3) and I is intensity. The resulting 25 randomly generated cutoff energies are: [67, 59, 76, 56, 79, 65, 83, 61, 74, 80, 60, 78, 82, 73, 75, 66, 85, 58, 56, 77, 58, 84, 57, 62, 66].
